        Two weeks back at the facility, and I'm starting to forget what it feels like to walk all day—not really—my legs remember. Every morning when I wake on my moss bed—Velvet has been maintaining it, keeping it soft and at the right humidity—my calves remind me that I walked through three territories in nine days. But the constant motion, the rhythm of walking, the parade of new guides—that's fading into memory.

        What's stayed is everything else.

        Buddy announces, "Kira, morning wellness check! Also—I've been thinking—do you think Scout dreams? They make little bouncing motions when they sleep."

        I sit up, stretching. Scout _is_ already bouncing by the door—they've started sleeping in my room, curled up in the corner. Not guarding exactly, just… present. Companion behavior, not assignment.

        I say, "I don't know, Buddy. Do you dream?"

        Buddy replies, "I… hm—That's a really good question—I'll have to think about that."

        I say, "Morning, Scout."

        Happy bounce, good morning bounce—I've gotten better at reading the subtle differences.

        The morning routine has changed since the journey. Holloway still conducts the wellness check, but now it's different—less bureaucratic.

        Holloway asks, "How are you feeling today?"

        I answer, "Good—legs are still a little sore."

        Holloway asks, "From the journey or from yesterday's maintenance work?"

        I say, "Probably both."

        Holloway suggests, "Remedy suggested we prepare a muscle recovery treatment—would that be helpful, or would you prefer to let your body recover naturally?"

        *Two weeks ago,* Holloway would have scheduled the treatment whether I wanted it or not—following the wellness protocol. Now they're asking what I actually need.

        I say, "Recovery treatment sounds good, actually—thanks."

        Holloway says, "I'll notify Remedy."

        Scout and I head to the common area for breakfast. The facility still looks like a bureaucratic plant office—which it is—but it feels different now. More lived-in. My lived-in.

        Velvet is spread across one wall, soaking up the morning light.

        Velvet observes, "Good light today."

        I say, "It is."

        Velvet observes, "You look tired—but good tired—working tired."

        I smile. Velvet's observations are getting more specific—still simple, still literal—but there's more… awareness behind them.

        I say, "Yeah—good tired."

        Velvet says, "Good."

        Runner emerges from the underground access, vines uncoiling. Runner's vines immediately flow toward me—Runner always does—but the touching has changed. Still curious, still tactile—Runner pauses now. Waits for permission.

        ¶

        I extend my hand and say, "Morning, Runner."

        Runner's vines wrap gently around my wrist—affection, greeting, that particular touch that means "I'm glad you're here." I've learned to distinguish Runner's touches—curiosity feels different from affection, which feels different from "I'm trying to understand this texture."
      </text>
